% Mathematics of Continuous Cellular Automata

% The existence of solitons, rotators and stable patterns in CCA's is a direct consequence of the symmetries of [CCA equation]. 

% Convolution with a radially-symmetric kernel is equivariant under rotation and translation, 

% The SE(2) symmetry comes from the fact that both A and K*A are equivariant under translation and rotation since the kernel is radially symmetric

% Formally, the PDE is equivariant under the action of the SE(2) and time translations. 

\section{Mathematical Results}

[CCA equation] \(\partial_tA=f(A,K\!*\!A)\) is equivariant under planar translations, rotations, and time shifts. Formally, it commutes with the Lie algebra
\[
\mathfrak g=\operatorname{span}_{\mathbb R}\{\partial_x, \partial_y, x\partial_y-y\partial_x, \partial_t\}.
\]

The translation and rotation symmetry is due to the properties of convolution and the radial symmetry of the kernel \(K\). The time translation symmetry follows from the fact that [CCA equation] is autonomous, meaning that $\partial_tA$ is independent of time. Using these symmetries, we can show that the ansatz $A(\mathbf{x},t)=e^{\gamma t}A_0,\, \gamma \in \mathfrak{g}, A_0=A(\mathbf{x},0)$ is a solution provided [stationary condition] is satisfied:

\begin{align}
    \partial_t\left[e^{\gamma t} A_0\right] &= f\left(e^{\gamma t} A_0, K * (e^{\gamma t} A_0)\right) \nonumber \\
    \gamma\,e^{\gamma t} A_0                &= f\left(e^{\gamma t} A_0, e^{\gamma t}(K*A_0)\right) \nonumber \\
    e^{\gamma t}\,\gamma A_0                &= e^{\gamma t}\,f\left(A_0, K*A_0\right) \nonumber \\
    \gamma A_0                              &= f\left(A_0, K*A_0\right) \label{stationary_cond}
\end{align}

Therefore, to find a translating solution $A(\mathbf{x},t)=A(\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{v}t,0)=e^{\gamma t}A_0,\,\mathbf{v} \in \mathbb{R}^2$, we need only find an initial field $A_0$ such that the stationary condition \eqref{stationary_cond} is satisfied with $\gamma=\mathbf{v}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}{\partial_x\\\partial_y}^\top\end{bmatrix}$.


